Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.554
Just wanted to begin today by
pointing out a couple of

00:00:04.554 --> 00:00:07.572
articles
from today's Boston Globe.

00:00:07.572 --> 00:00:11.000
There's an article that's on
the financial

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:14.616
pages about investors
reconsidering gene therapy,

00:00:14.616 --> 00:00:18.059
and startups funded as
technology evolves.

00:00:18.059 --> 00:00:22.000
A lot of you have heard the
words gene therapy.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:25.221
A lot of you,
at the end of that bacterial

00:00:25.221 --> 00:00:27.500
genetics lecture,
said you

00:00:27.500 --> 00:00:33.000
weren't quite sure what
complementation was.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:37.379
But, gene therapy is basically
complementation put to work.

00:00:37.379 --> 00:00:39.669
The
idea is if you got a broken

00:00:39.669 --> 00:00:42.664
gene, and you can put in a good
copy, then

00:00:42.664 --> 00:00:45.455
you'll take the cell back to
being normal,

00:00:45.455 --> 00:00:49.548
which is exactly what we're
doing in those phage crosses

00:00:49.548 --> 00:00:52.332
where we had two phage,
one with the

00:00:52.332 --> 00:00:56.130
mutant copy of the gene,
and one with the wild type copy

00:00:56.130 --> 00:00:57.166
of the gene.

00:00:57.166 --> 00:01:02.000
And they're saying here that
there's a renewed interest.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.733
Now, the basic strategy in
these things is to take usually

00:01:06.733 --> 00:01:09.121
a
retrovirus, the same kind of

00:01:09.121 --> 00:01:12.132
idea that we heard about with
the HIV-1

00:01:12.132 --> 00:01:16.340
virus that will make a DNA
copy, and then the copy gets

00:01:16.340 --> 00:01:19.284
inserted
somewhere in the chromosome.

00:01:19.284 --> 00:01:22.263
So, the good thing is it puts
in a new

00:01:22.263 --> 00:01:23.828
copy in a chromosome.

00:01:23.828 --> 00:01:27.330
The bad thing is you got a
piece of DNA being

00:01:27.330 --> 00:01:29.652
stuck somewhere in the
chromosome.

00:01:29.652 --> 00:01:32.397
And there are places where it
can go

00:01:32.397 --> 00:01:36.552
where it doesn't matter,
and there are other places

00:01:36.552 --> 00:01:38.866
where it
really does matter.

00:01:38.866 --> 00:01:41.666
So, it's been a very tricky
business

00:01:41.666 --> 00:01:42.548
with gene therapy.

00:01:42.548 --> 00:01:44.998
Part of the thrust here is
they're thinking that

00:01:44.998 --> 00:01:47.783
maybe they need to pick targets
were the person's going to die

00:01:47.783 --> 00:01:49.534
anyway so
that if there is a risk of

00:01:49.534 --> 00:01:51.665
getting cancer or something,
it's outweighed

00:01:51.665 --> 00:01:52.776
by the possible thing.

00:01:52.776 --> 00:01:54.089
That's sort of the thrust.

00:01:54.089 --> 00:01:56.589
You can see the
article; it's in today's paper.

00:01:56.589 --> 00:01:58.333
It's very timely for what we
are

00:01:58.333 --> 00:01:59.668
talking about now.

00:01:59.668 --> 00:02:03.992
And then on Friday I'm going to
start talking about recombinant

00:02:03.992 --> 00:02:05.504
DNA strategies and stuff.

00:02:05.504 --> 00:02:07.946
But there's
another article in today's

00:02:07.946 --> 00:02:08.314
paper.

00:02:08.314 --> 00:02:10.585
This is one of those things
that I

00:02:10.585 --> 00:02:13.808
told you about where an article
is published in the,

00:02:13.808 --> 00:02:16.626
in this case,
online in the journal Nature.

00:02:16.626 --> 00:02:19.056
They have an embargo on a press
thing

00:02:19.056 --> 00:02:21.960
until Thursday or so,
and then the article is on,

00:02:21.960 --> 00:02:25.022
the hot papers that
have just come out show up in

00:02:25.022 --> 00:02:27.527
the newspapers,
usually either on Friday

00:02:27.527 --> 00:02:28.124
or Monday.

00:02:28.124 --> 00:02:31.764
And this is yet another system
that they describe as making

00:02:31.764 --> 00:02:35.608
a molecular repair kit that
corrects mutations in the cells'

00:02:35.608 --> 00:02:36.000
DNA.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:38.539
So far, this has only been done
in cells.

00:02:38.539 --> 00:02:41.485
But it's working well
enough, and the article is

00:02:41.485 --> 00:02:44.000
saying this approach could
become a serious

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.363
competitor to conventional gene
therapy.

00:02:46.363 --> 00:02:49.850
In here, you have sort of
a layman's account of this kind

00:02:49.850 --> 00:02:52.000
of complementation by gene
therapy.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:54.914
We're talking about gene
therapy in that field which

00:02:54.914 --> 00:02:57.812
attempts to force
feed healthy genes into cells

00:02:57.812 --> 00:03:00.000
hobbled by defective ones has
been

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.333
plagued by failure,
and recently was found to cause

00:03:03.333 --> 00:03:05.416
leukemia
in some patients.

00:03:05.416 --> 00:03:09.840
That's probably because of the
insertion events associated

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:11.077
with these viruses.

00:03:11.077 --> 00:03:14.197
This new system
rewrites the small stretch of

00:03:14.197 --> 00:03:15.810
misspelled genetic code.

00:03:15.810 --> 00:03:18.165
That's
typically the reason the gene

00:03:18.165 --> 00:03:18.950
has gone bad.

00:03:18.950 --> 00:03:21.338
So it's a different kind
of strategy.

00:03:21.338 --> 00:03:24.053
This is the first report I've
heard of that.

00:03:24.053 --> 00:03:26.525
Some of
the stuff we're talking about

00:03:26.525 --> 00:03:28.915
is sort of inescapable because
you're

00:03:28.915 --> 00:03:30.614
going to see it in the paper.

00:03:30.614 --> 00:03:32.722
Here, they're telling you the
sort

00:03:32.722 --> 00:03:34.152
of thing I was just saying.

00:03:34.152 --> 00:03:36.166
The viruses inject their
payloads at

00:03:36.166 --> 00:03:39.133
random within the cell's mass
of DNA sometimes disrupting

00:03:39.133 --> 00:03:39.901
normal
genes.

00:03:39.901 --> 00:03:42.423
Even when genes land in good
locations, the molecular

00:03:42.423 --> 00:03:44.522
machinery
that regulates their activity

00:03:44.522 --> 00:03:46.497
is also often thrown off,
leaving the

00:03:46.497 --> 00:03:49.272
healthy genes operating at a
level too low to be helpful or

00:03:49.272 --> 00:03:51.489
functioning
in the wrong parts of the body.

00:03:51.489 --> 00:03:53.036
It must begin to sound
familiar.

00:03:53.036 --> 00:03:54.962
You
stick a random piece of DNA

00:03:54.962 --> 00:03:58.582
somewhere, you can disrupt the
regulation in the gene as well

00:03:58.582 --> 00:04:01.329
as just landing in the open
reading frame.

00:04:01.329 --> 00:04:04.138
So there's a problem with gene
therapy.

00:04:04.138 --> 00:04:07.207
Now, they'd like to make you
think that this is going to be

00:04:07.207 --> 00:04:09.710
the promise to everything,
but as always it's more

00:04:09.710 --> 00:04:10.323
complicated.

00:04:10.323 --> 00:04:12.280
And
so, I just picked up the last

00:04:12.280 --> 00:04:13.713
paragraph of this article.

00:04:13.713 --> 00:04:15.544
Other
scientists said the approach

00:04:15.544 --> 00:04:17.629
looked promising,
but predicted it would

00:04:17.629 --> 00:04:19.848
end up struggling with this
problem of its own,

00:04:19.848 --> 00:04:20.234
James M.

00:04:20.234 --> 00:04:22.399
Wilson, a gene
therapy researcher at the

00:04:22.399 --> 00:04:23.799
University of Pennsylvania.

00:04:23.799 --> 00:04:26.233
Now, there's
somebody who's in a position to

00:04:26.233 --> 00:04:29.176
criticize, but also has a vested
interest himself in the

00:04:29.176 --> 00:04:31.524
alternative therapy,
noted that the first step

00:04:31.524 --> 00:04:35.000
of the new process causes for
zinc fingers.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:38.094
It's a kind of protein that's
involved in this,

00:04:38.094 --> 00:04:41.241
to make a fresh
break in DNA to accommodate the

00:04:41.241 --> 00:04:43.613
insertion of the corrected
sequence.

00:04:43.613 --> 00:04:47.288
It's the same kind of break
with radiation that can lead to

00:04:47.288 --> 00:04:47.922
cancer.

00:04:47.922 --> 00:04:51.122
And we're going to talk today
about, you'll see where

00:04:51.122 --> 00:04:53.891
double-stranded
breaks and whatnot can be a

00:04:53.891 --> 00:04:56.538
real problem in terms of the
integrity of

00:04:56.538 --> 00:04:59.909
the DNA and genome stability,
which is maintaining gene

00:04:59.909 --> 00:05:03.230
stability so
important in avoiding cancer.

